column8: 110074 Human Research Trials Head and Footwell Heating
column35:
We'd like to conduct some simulation tests before any further testing. The goal is to determine whether the MSP can achieve good comfort with reasonable power consumption. If not, no further test is needed.
h3. Simulation test conditions:
 * i3 model with MSP panels.
 * winter outdoor temperature.

h3. simulation conditions/steps:

Step 1: simulation with HVAC only (highest setpoint maybe?), calculate how much heat is needed on feet surface to achieve occupant comfort.

 

Step 2: Simulation with MSP only, calculate how much power consumption is needed to have feet surface reach the same comfort/surface temperature 

 

Step 3: Simulation with lower HVAC setpoint+MSP(may not needed, calculate how much power consumption may be saved to have feet surface reach the same comfort /surface temperature with full HVAC)

 

Variables should recorded:
 * Thermal comfort/Sensation
 * cabin temperature
 * Feet area cloth surface temperature
 * Feet skin surface temperature
 * power consumed by HVAC or device
 * Heat transfer
 

 

 

Other considerations:

How to integrate MSP in i3? MSP can not be cut but can be bent. how to work around the HVAC vent?

Does our current size of MSP work? Does it need to be smaller? what size is better, with a smaller size, can it achieve anything comfort?

breakdown of what the entry likely covers:

*Notification Webhook Functionality:*

It enables external systems or applications to receive automated notifications from ROOK.
This is likely a subscription-based service, where users provide a URL (endpoint) to which ROOK sends notifications.
It facilitates real-time event-driven communication.

*Use Cases:*


Potential use cases include:
Alerting users to specific events (e.g., data processing completion, errors).
Integrating ROOK with other systems for automated workflows.
Enabling real-time data synchronization.;;;

column1: Default handler issue with sudden reset with IAR
column35:
Analysis/Overview:
It has been observed that initiating a sudden reset from IAR leads to data corruption in the EEPROM and causes the control to transition to the default handler state.

After consulting with TI regarding this issue, they advised against performing sudden resets. However, for real-time scenarios where sudden resets are unavoidable, TI has proposed a potential solution to mitigate this issue.

The purpose of this ticket is to evaluate and implement the solution provided by TI, ensuring system stability during such scenarios.


estimate time: 3 days

Done criteria

how is it tested?
Validation to be done on the Hardware.

Load the program and set it to free run.
Open the Lin simulation, import MCF8316C_registers(default) JSON file and send the WriteDataSet command.
Check all motor config parameters are Writing into EEPROM.
Send ReadDataSet command and check EEPROM read.

Code reviewed by.
TBD

PR created.
TBD

MUFU_TaskH()

column1: Debug and Fix EEPROM issue for ERROR Mapper Integration
column35:
Analysis/Overview:
After multiple resets from IAR workbench, the control is going to default handler state.
This is because, after this reset the ErrorMapper data is writing into EEPROM.
The data should write into memory after ECU Sleep, so that whatever data in queue will be written into memory. 

The validation needs to be performed with Sleep and Wakeup signals and test for default handler issue.

estimate time: 1 day

Done criteria

how is it tested?
Needs to find the root cause and fix.

Code reviewed by.
TBD

PR created.
TBD

Description:

Effort estimate:
1 Day

Tasks to be done:
-> Validation with Sleep and Wakeup signals using Canoe+Lin
column44:
The default handler issues not seen with sleep and wakeup signal. 
The control going to default handle state with reset from IAR workbench.
We sent an email to TI, once we get the proper confirmation on how to handle this scenario will work on it;04/Mar/25 1:13 AM;ext.roopavathi.linga;180
column46: Validated more than 30 times with sleep and wakeup signals, the control is not entering into Default handler state.;06/Mar/25 8:44 AM;ext.roopavathi.linga;32400
column668:
Validated more than 30 times, default handler issues not seen with sleep and wakeup signal. 
The control going to default handle state with reset from IAR workbench.
We sent an email to TI on how to handle this scenario.
column724:
03/Mar/25 9:00 AM;ext.roopavathi.linga;Validation Summary:
-> Validated the EEPROM and ErrorMapper with Sleep and Wakeup signals.
-> Ran the code without any breakpoints.
-> Sent Sleep and Wakeup signals multiple times to ensure stability.
-> Observed that control is not going to the default handler state.
-> The latest error flag from ErrorMapper is successfully written into the memory after sleep.
-> Code runs smoothly and performs all EEPROM operations as expected during unit testing.

;;;

column1: [On Hold]Issue with Watchdog Timer on L1228 Board Causing Low Power State
column35:
The watchdog timer application setup has been created and validated on the G3507 board, where it is working as expected. The same setup was then migrated to the G3107 board, and it also worked as expected. However, when the same code is migrated to the L1228 board, the board goes into an unknown state. This issue prevents flashing new code, and the device needs to be put into normal state by invoking the Boot Strap Loader (BSL). Immediate attention is required to resolve this issue.

*Steps to Reproduce:*
 # Create and validate the watchdog timer application setup on the G3507 board.
 # Migrate the setup to the G3107 board and validate its functionality.
 # Migrate the same setup to the L1228 board.
 # Observe the board going into an unknown state, preventing further code flashing.

*Expected Result:* The watchdog timer application should work as expected on the L1228 board, similar to its performance on the G3507 and G3107 boards.

*Actual Result:* The L1228 board goes into an unknown state, requiring BSL invocation to return to normal state.

column724:
31/Jan/25 12:08 PM;ext.rohit.saligram;the Offstate diagnostics status bit seems to be stable now with new HW changes. 

Online Diagnostics status bits needs to be checked against the HW changes;;;
column725:
05/Feb/25 2:43 AM;ext.rohit.saligram;Here are the steps suggested by TI team. We need to remove following highlighted components in 3 steps and observe the behavior of the Chip.

!TI_Recommendation_DRV8242_STeps_From_HW.png!;;;
column726:
05/Feb/25 2:44 AM;ext.rohit.saligram;We divided the step1 hardware changes in to sub steps and Here's the behavior.
 
__
|1.1|Removed R33|OLP_CMP stopped toggling. Online OLA is still being set when pump is running|
|1.2|Removed R45|Online OLA is still being set when pump is running|
|1.3|Removed D9|Online OLA is still being set when pump is running|
 
To summarize after step1, in off-state diagnostics the OLP_CMP toggling is fixed as soon as R33 was removed. In On-state still we see a fault being set when pump is running. The fault is identified to be OLA (open load) and its detected on Output 2.;;;
column727:
13/Feb/25 3:44 AM;ext.rohit.saligram;We have followed the steps suggested by TI and still we don't see any improvement on Online Open load diagnostics. 

As suggested by HW team, We removed the Voltage dividers on Out1 and Out2. Still there's no improvement. 

Next step would be to populate inductor and Capacitor on Out2 and see the behavior of the chip.

This will be handled by HW engineer. We need to procure ar receive these components.

I will link the HW related ticket here once created.;;;

R:6.1.6.1.1 The MCS System shall record the ambient temperature when Key_In_Igni...109785-932 - R:6.1.6.1.1 The MCS System shall record the ambient temperature when Key_In_Ignition_Stat transitions from OUT to IN (to act as a baseline).R:6.1.6.1.2 If the new recorded ambient temperature differs from the previous re...109785-939 - R:6.1.6.1.2 If the new recorded ambient temperature differs from the previous recorded ambient temperature by X ˚C (configurable parameter DE00:Delta Ambient Temperature), the MCS System shall initiate a rebuild.R:6.1.6.1.3 While Key_In_Ignition_Stat = IN, if the current ambient temperature...109785-933 - R:6.1.6.1.3 While Key_In_Ignition_Stat = IN, if the current ambient temperature differs from the recorded ambient temperature by X ˚C (configurable parameter DE00:Delta Ambient Temperature), the MCS System shall record the current ambient temperature (as the new baseline) and initiate a rebuild.

column45:
5.11.2.1 Relative Bladder PressureRelative bladder pressure is the difference between a single bladder’s absolute pressure and the ambient atmospheric pressure measured in kPa.R:6.1.7.1.1 The pressure for a single bladder shall be calculated by subtracting...109785-942 - R:6.1.7.1.1 The pressure for a single bladder shall be calculated by subtracting the recorded ambient pressure from the current absolute pressure of a bladder (as reported by that bladder’s pressure sensor).

5.11.2.2 Bladder Pressure ReportingThe pressures of the manually adjustable bladders are reported out over CAN.  For single bladders, like the lumbar bladders, this is a straightforward process.  The bolster bladders – the Upper Bolster and the Lower Bolster – are sets of bladders: there are two bladders in the Upper Bolster and two bladders in the Lower Bolster.  Each set is meant to be viewed as one unit, though they actually operate in parallel; as such, the single pressure reported for each bolster bladder set is actually an average of the two.R:6.1.7.2.1 The MCS System shall report the relative pressures for the manually...109785-946 - R:6.1.7.2.1 The MCS System shall report the relative pressures for the manually adjustable bladders as a percentage of the maximum bladder pressure (see the configurable parameters in DID DE04).R:6.1.7.2.2 The relative pressure of the Upper Bolster shall be the average of t...109785-945 - R:6.1.7.2.2 The relative pressure of the Upper Bolster shall be the average of the relative pressures of the Right Upper Bolster and the Left Upper Bolster.R:6.1.7.2.3 The pressure of the Lower Bolster shall be the average of the relati...109785-948 - R:6.1.7.2.3 The pressure of the Lower Bolster shall be the average of the relative pressures of the Right Lower Bolster and the Left Lower Bolster.;14/Mar/25 8:02 AM;ext.satyavathi.datla;32400

R:6.1.4.2.1 When the MCS System detects a pump circuit failure, it shall turn of...109785-922 - R:6.1.4.2.1 When the MCS System detects a pump circuit failure, it shall turn off power to the pump and set the Pump Driver Failure DTC.R:6.1.4.2.2 After a pump circuit failure is detected, MCS module 1.) shall ignor...109785-925 - R:6.1.4.2.2 After a pump circuit failure is detected, MCS module 1.) shall ignore increase or decrease manual adjustment commands; 2.) shall not perform rebuilds; 3.) shall not execute selected massage profiles; 4.) shall not perform deflation on transition to Easy Entry Exit mode.R:6.1.4.2.3 A new ignition cycle (Ignition Status transitions from RUN to OFF to...109785-924 - R:6.1.4.2.3 A new ignition cycle (Ignition Status transitions from RUN to OFF to RUN again) shall allow for the above functionality to be reinstated and for the pump to be retried.  Upon successful activation of the pump, the MSC3 System shall remove the Pump Driver Failure DTC from active status.;07/Mar/25 1:53 AM;ext.satyavathi.datla;32400

worked on:

R:6.1.1.51 The System shall set a Stuck Button DTC when the same non-NULL switch...109785-836 - R:6.1.1.51 The System shall set a Stuck Button DTC when the same non-NULL switch command has been continuously received for a configurable amount of time (configurable parameter Stuck Switch DTC Setting Time).R:6.1.1.5.2 When a Stuck Button DTC is set all non-NULL switch commands shall be...109785-835 - R:6.1.1.5.2 When a Stuck Button DTC is set all non-NULL switch commands shall be ignored until a NULL switch command has been received or a power reset has occurred.;07/Mar/25 1:52 AM;ext.satyavathi.datla;16200

column35:
Test specification development - 5.1.1 Analog Switch
R:6.1.1.1.1 Inputs from the analog switch shall only be processed when the parameter Switch Type is configured to ANALOG
R:6.1.1.1.2 UP, DOWN, and SELECT commands shall be processed only once on transition from NULL.
R:6.1.1.1.3 In Manual Adjustment Mode, INCREASE and DECREASE commands shall be processed for as long as the button is held when transitioning from NULL.
R:6.1.1.1.4 In Massage Mode, INCREASE and DECREASE commands shall be processed only once per button press when transitioning from NULL.
R:6.1.1.1.5 When the input from the analog switch is OPEN, the MCS System shall set the Seat Switch Input Failure (Open) DTC.
R:6.1.1.1.6 When the input from the analog switch is SHORT, the MCS System shall set the Seat Switch Input Failure (Short) DTC

Download the document and mark it with your review comments for any rejected parts of the specification.

Based on the CyberSecurity Relevancy Assessment, Ford shall provide the following:
• Cybersecurity Relevant category
• Cybersecurity Preliminary Risk Assessment which determines secure boot application strategy

column1: Determine if Software is the source of Drift
column35: Determine if there is any possibility of edge detections being missed by the MCU.
column577: 13/Mar/25 3:19 PM;andranik.melikyan;3_12_25_BMW ZIM Drift Testing data_Horizontal Only_256 cycles_Displacement.xlsx;https://jira.gentherm.com/secure/attachment/62248/3_12_25_BMW+ZIM+Drift+Testing+data_Horizontal+Only_256+cycles_Displacement.xlsx
column724:
13/Mar/25 11:48 AM;223460;From SW perspective:

We increment the position counts based on the Hall interrupts, increasing the counts the number of interrupts we are getting directly from the hall, the value is stored in the array hallCount which later is copied to be added or subtracted from the current position count accordingly. so, this value was supervised while commanding the motor through target positioning from position 2500 to position 3500, bellow the results:

!image-2025-03-13-11-46-48-537.png!
As can be seen, the same number of interrupts happen all the time when going to same point A to same point B, this is telling us the interrupts are consistent at least when ideal conditions no over temperature or stress.;;;
column725:
13/Mar/25 11:51 AM;223460;Additional information from the test is needed to perform a deeper analysis, such as determining if the drift is caused by a false stall detected, since when that happens when moving backwards from SW we forced position to be 0 assuming we hit the hardstop (need from DSM5 project), but is hard to determine if this is happening without enough data.

From SW perspective to perform a deeper analysis, we need:
 * Hall information
 * Correlation between potentiometer measurements and target position commanded
 * CAN traces

[~andranik.melikyan] Could you please provide above information?

 ;;;
column727: 14/Mar/25 1:00 PM;223460;From the logs provided is clear to me the first drift happened while moving rearward, that makes me think we are falsely detecting stall, causing the SW to reset the current position to 0 under the assumption we hit the end of the track, this event happened after 5 hours and 40 minutes, unfortunately to confirm this we need the CAN traces so we can track the motor status, CAN traces not provided for this specific scenario.;;;
column728: 14/Mar/25 1:10 PM;223460;This morning a verification was made on the instrumentation and test setup, we realized that the test was using the actual end of the track at M3 position still uncertain how this was assumed as 40 hall counts, we modify the setup and triggered the test again but now matching 0 position from track to define a new M3 as 150 Hall counts something that was measured as 38.3 by the potentiometer, so now the test should iterate between 38.3 and 274.9, this should be enough to avoid any stall if this was caused by a physical limitation.;;;
column729:
14/Mar/25 1:51 PM;andranik.melikyan;Re-tested on 3-13 and observed about 20 mm drift. xls file with linear potentiometer displacement, current from the Horizontal motor and hall sensor voltage as well as CAN logs are located in Confluence - > [https://confluence.gentherm.com/display/109742/BMW+ZIM+Drift+testing+results]

.;;;

11/Mar/25 12:52 PM;Karim.Andreu;[~Alexander.Rappl] [~223460] [~michael.seck] : I measured the ramps today in target positioning. Please check the attached power point for details
 # Current profile is much better, avoiding extreme peaks
 # Acoustic perception is very much improved

I only found a problem: some motors do get stalled when starting the movement. I believe the reason is that the first 50% duty cycle plateau might no be enough energy to move the motor. I will create a bug for it.

Motor 08 did not move anymore after the absolute positioning routine, nor manually nor with target position (not even at 100% DC and 16V). My assumption is that the motor needs more energy to get out of the stalle condition, and with this ramp start at 50% might not be enough. I replaced the ECU with SW R2.0.0 and I could get the motor moving.

I could see this behavior in Motor 07;;;

column1: PWM Ramp up/down update as per proposal
column35: The idea of this story is to keep track of the progress on the modifications requested for ramp up/down
column44: Analysis and implementation ;11/Mar/25 10:18 AM;223460;28800
column724:
11/Mar/25 10:17 AM;223460;Ramp up/down implementation has been updated as follows:

Ramp-up:
 * Applicable for Manual and Auto movements
 * 1st step and minimum PWM to be applied while ramping up is 50%
 * The entire ramp up should be executed within 200 ms
 * Number of steps is determined by Ramp Up Duration (200ms) / 20 (runnable periodicity in ms)
 * Step size is defined as (TargetedPWM - 50(min pwm)/ # of Rampup steps (described above)

Ramp-down:
 * Applicable for Auto movements only
 * Ramp down duration will be last 20 hall counts before reaching target position
 * Re usage of step size from ramp up for, applied as 2 times step size (ramp up) each ramp down step.
 * Minimum PWM to be applied is 50% to avoid risking target positioning accuracy due to a false stall;;;
column725: 17/Mar/25 2:16 PM;223460;After some stalls detected by [~Karim.Andreu] on issue P109742-571 the initial PWM applied when ramping up changed from 50% to 60%, this change was made on commit 428f691, a new engineering release will be created for testing purposes (ENG_3.0.1).;;;

column1: The ECU resets all 0xFDA2 and all 0xFDA3 values to 0 (default) when it transitions from Extended to default session
column35:
The ECU resets all 0xFDA2 values to 0 (default) when it transitions from Extended to default session.

 

+*How to reproduce:*+
 # Enter Extended Session
 # Write values in service 0xFDA2 and 0xFDA3 and make sure the ECU sends positive response

column1: ECU cannot activate eFuse 02 when there is a load connected
column35:
ECU cannot activate eFuse 02 when there is a load connected.

If there is no load connected, the ECU outputs a voltage when the eFuse 02 is activated (OK), but if there is a load connected, the ECU fails to activate it the output. This works well with eFuse 01.

+*How to reproduce (@13.5V):*+
 # Activate eFuse 02 without any connected Load --> The ECU outputs voltage on eFuse output (OK)
 # Deactivate eFuse 02
 # Connect a Load which can draw variable current (i.e. 1A, 2A...7A) to the eFuse 02 output of the ECU. It can also be a heater mat but the resistance should have a value where no more than 7.5A flows
 # Activate eFuse 02 --> *The ECU does not apply any voltage. No DTCs recorded.* +*Seat1DeFuse2Ctrl_En_Stat* is set to *Active* though+

+*Expected:*+ The ECU should work as in eFuse 01 and apply voltage to the connected Load
column673: Wrong GND pin connection defined in the schematic. Layout is ok
column724:
07/Mar/25 8:07 AM;Alexander.Rappl;[~michael.seck] what is the feedback from TI to this issue?

 ;;;
column725:
07/Mar/25 8:25 AM;michael.seck;TI was in-house to assist with debugging this issue.

Using 1.4ohm power resistors during debug.

Both eFuse1 and eFuse2 were blown when connected to 5.6ohm resistive load (2.4A)

Odd behavior:
 * During testing eFuse1 did not have 12V or draw current when activated
 * Used DMM to confirm test harness

During investigation it was found that the ECU tested didn't have eFuse modifications

After modifications,
 * eFuse2 activated normally (holding steady at 4.8A and blowing when exposed to 8.5A)
 * eFuse1 had the same behavior from pre-mod testing (0V and no current draw when activated)
 ** When connecting eFuse1 PWR with eFuse2 GND, eFuse1 operates normally (holding steady at 4.8A and blowing when exposed to 8.5A)

Conclusions:
 * 
 ** [~Karim.Andreu] : Confirm that the e-Load that you are using is not causing issues (such as an in-rush).  Potentially caused if there is a capacitor in the e-load.
 ** [~Karim.Andreu] : Retest after connecting eFuse1 and eFuse2 GNDs (should be connected inside ECU)
 ** [~justin.frim] : Check the ECU / routing of eFuse1 to see if there is a mfg or design issue with eFuse2 GND;;;

column1: The ECU sets the Motor Status signal to AXIS_BUSY upon movement request, although the Motor Duty Cycle is 0%
column35:
The ECU sets the Motor Status signal to AXIS_BUSY upon movement request, although the Motor Duty Cycle is 0%.

The Motor Status signal is set to AXIS_BUSY for 4s, then it gets back to AXIS_IDLE.

*+How to reproduce:+*
 # Send 0% duty cycle to any motor and wait until the ECU confirms the 0% in the Motor Status signal
 # Trigger manual movement on the same motor and observe the Motor status signal how it changes to AXIS_BUSY for 4s and then changes to AXIS_IDLE.

+*Expected:*+ Since the motor has 0% duty cycle, it is expected that the motor status signal remains at AXIS_IDLE, as with 0% duty cycle a motor cannot move

column1: eFuses Status are not set to Inactive when in Standby State
column35:
eFuses Status are not set to Inactive when in Standby State.

After Powering up the ECU the eFuses Status signals are as follows:
 * Seat1DeFuse1Ctrl_En_Stat = Inactive (OK)
 * Seat1DeFuse2Ctrl_En_Stat = *Active* (NOTOK)
 * Seat1DeFuse3Ctrl_En_Stat = *Blown* (NOTOK)
 * Seat1DeFuse4Ctrl_En_Stat = *Fault* (NOTOK)
 * Seat1DeFuse5Ctrl_En_Stat = *Blown* (NOTOK)
 * Seat1DeFuse6Ctrl_En_Stat = *Active* (NOTOK)

+*Expected:*+ The eFuses Status all shall be set to Inactive, when in Standby State.

 

From Testing side we are aware that eFuses are still not implemented in ENG.0.1.0, but we expect at least that the CAN signals are set to Inactive even if the function is not implemented.
column724: 11/Feb/25 9:28 AM;223460;[~Karim.Andreu] this should be fixed by ENG 2.1.0, please verify;;;
column725:
12/Feb/25 2:25 AM;Karim.Andreu;Issue solved in ENG_2.1.0:

Create, set up, and link all Azure resources in accordance with the previously developed RAG architecture.
column35:
Based on the previously built architecture, create and configure the Azure resources needed to implement RAG PoC.
 # Azure Blob storage
 # Azure event grid
 # Azure functions

h4. Day 1 (17-March): Azure Blob Storage
 * {*}Objective{*}: Set up Azure Blob Storage for storing data and documents required for the RAG model.
 * {*}Tasks{*}:
 ** Create a new Azure Blob Storage account.
 ** Configure containers for different types of data (e.g., raw data, processed data).
 ** Set up access policies and permissions.
 ** Upload initial data samples for testing.

h4. Day 2 (18-March): Azure Event Grid
 * {*}Objective{*}: Configure Azure Event Grid to handle events and notifications related to data changes in Blob Storage.
 * {*}Tasks{*}:
 ** Create an Event Grid topic.
 ** Set up event subscriptions for Blob Storage events (e.g., blob creation, deletion).
 ** Configure filters and routing rules for events.
 ** Test event handling with sample data changes.

h4. Day 3 (19-March): Azure Functions (Part 1)
 * {*}Objective{*}: Develop Azure Functions to process events from Event Grid and interact with Blob Storage.
 * {*}Tasks{*}:
 ** Create a new Azure Function App.
 ** Develop functions to handle Blob Storage events (e.g., data processing, indexing).
 ** Configure function triggers based on Event Grid events.
 ** Test functions with sample events.

h4. Day 4 (20-March): Azure Functions (Part 2)
 * {*}Objective{*}: Enhance Azure Functions for additional processing and integration with the RAG model.
 * {*}Tasks{*}:
 ** Implement additional functions for data transformation and enrichment.
 ** Integrate functions with the RAG model components.
 ** Set up logging and monitoring for functions.
 ** Test end-to-end workflow from Blob Storage to RAG model.

h4. Day 5 (21-March): Final Testing and Documentation
 * {*}Objective{*}: Perform final testing and document the setup and configuration.
 * {*}Tasks{*}:
 ** Conduct comprehensive testing of all components (Blob Storage, Event Grid, Functions).
 ** Resolve any issues or bugs identified during testing.
 ** Document the setup process, configurations, and any troubleshooting steps.
 ** Prepare a summary report for the PoC implementation.

column1: Look into end to end architecture of hosting the data for RAG model
column35: Look into how to host the data online for the RAG model. The architecture should be such that there should be a location that hosts the data in raw format. Anytime there is a change in the data, an encoder converts the data to a vector format and stores it in another location. Whenever a query is made, the model uses the vector store data.

column45: I explored how to extract text data from PDF files for a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) model using Azure AI Document Intelligence and open-source Python libraries. Azure AI offers advanced models like the Read Model and Layout Model for OCR and structural data extraction. Open-source libraries such as PDFMiner, PyPDF2, PDFQuery, and PyMuPDF are also effective for text extraction. Once extracted, the text can be semantically chunked and indexed using tools like Elasticsearch or Azure Cognitive Search, enabling efficient retrieval and generation of responses in a RAG model.;11/Mar/25 11:43 PM;ext.nagesh.machara;32400
column46: Generated embeddings using models as part of the RAG LLM development. column1: Identify online vector storage for keeping RAG data
column35:
Identify and implement resources to convert RAG data into a vector format for efficient storage and retrieval. This will ensure the process does not need to be repeated, enhancing data management and accessibility.

*Steps:*
 # *Explore Vector Store Models (Due: 3-March)*

 * 
 ** Research various vector store models.
 ** Evaluate their compatibility with the existing Proof of Concept (PoC).
 ** Select the most suitable model for integration.

 # *Implement PoC with FAISS Vector Store (Due: 4-March)*

 * 
 ** Integrate the selected vector store model with the existing PoC.
 ** Implement a Proof of Concept (PoC) using the FAISS vector store database.
 ** Ensure the FAISS vector store can effectively store and manage RAG data.
 * *Implement PoC with ANNOY Vector Store (Due: 5-March)*
 ** Integrate the selected vector store model with the existing PoC.
 ** Implement a Proof of Concept (PoC) using the ANNOY vector store database.
 ** Ensure the ANNOY vector store can effectively store and manage RAG data.
 * *Implement PoC with Qdrant Vector Store (Due: 6-March)*
 ** Integrate the selected vector store model with the existing PoC.
 ** Implement a Proof of Concept (PoC) using the Qdrant vector store database.
 ** Ensure the Qdrant vector store can effectively store and manage RAG data.
 * {*}Identify which vector store is feasible for the existing PoC{*}. *(Due: 7-March)*
 ** Tried and validated open source vector stores that are feasible for existing RAG poc.
 ** Found that FAISS vector store implementation is easy and performing well

*Expected Output:* Identify and create a vector store that can store RAG data.
*Achievement:* Create FAISS vector store that keeps RAG data and saves it as an external file for efficient storage and retrieval.
column44: Exploring vector databases to store RAG data. Weaviate: An open-source vector database with strong support for metadata filtering and modular vector search. It offers a RESTful API and supports multiple vectorization modules. Milvus: A highly scalable and feature-rich open-source vector database designed for high-performance search. It can handle billions of vectors, making it ideal for large-scale RAG systems. Vespa: An open-source big data serving engine that supports real-time indexing and search. It is optimized for handling large-scale vector search and retrieval;04/Mar/25 9:29 AM;ext.nagesh.machara;32400

column48:
Explored vector database models to store RAG data. Implemented base model with ANNOY.

ANNOY (Approximate Nearest Neighbors Oh Yeah): Its a C++ library with Python bindings to search for points in space that are close to a given query point. It also creates large read-only file-based data structures that are mapped into memory so that many processes may share the same data.

column1: Integrate, Review and Verify resolution of listed bugs - Part 2 (Final Release)
column35:
Bug report:

*Main page* 
  - Seat images need to be switched (Nishanth should have emailed these already, let me know if not received)
  - Set temperatures need to also change when going from degC to degF
  - Climatesense legend colors need to be swapped (the blue and white from the legend need to be swapped)

*Metrics page* 
  - Duration on the metrics page increases too quickly, needs to be matched with the clock of the device. Please use a datetime class (or similar) to implement this to avoid any inconsistencies
  - After clicking power off and reentering climatesense/standard mode, a new data collection session should start (currently it shows previous run's data)
  - In standard mode, neck should be unchecked by default when tapping a profile to view graph
  - Clicking on one of the tiles for the whole seat on the metrics page should bring up graph for the whole seat (just as in the graph page)

*Profile/Settings page*
  - Settings from settings page for the device toggles (on/off) needs to be connected to the profile data (look below for formatting help)
  - 1 profile can only be selected by 1 side (driver/passenger) at a time
  - Profile deletion was working only after "power off" and back to "climatesense" mode. It needs to be deleted as soon as the user hits delete
  - Send profile data from the currently selected profile to websocket in following format:

 

{     UI_R1L_EHR_tOffset: offset_val ;     UI_R1L_ESB_tOffset: offset_val ;     UI_R1L_ESC_tOffset: offset_val ;     UI_R1R_EHR_tOffset: offset_val ;     UI_R1R_ESB_tOffset: offset_val ;     UI_R1R_ESC_tOffset: offset_val ;     UI_R1L_EHR_enSmartEff: en_val ;     UI_R1L_ESB_enSmartEff: en_val ;     UI_R1L_ESC_enSmartEff: en_val ;     UI_R1R_EHR_enSmartEff: en_val ;     UI_R1R_ESB_enSmartEff: en_val ;     UI_R1R_ESC_enSmartEff: en_val ; }

 

where offset_val is an int between -3 and 3 denoting user selection
where en_val is either the string "ENABLED" or "DISABLED" denoting user selection

 

Also a general comment, behavior has become a little sluggish, response from a tap is slightly delayed taking almost a second (especially when filtering the graphs). Not really a functional bug but still something we need to look into.

List of new bugs found in second to latest release (3/10/25):
 * Intro screen can be swiped across to go to next/previous page. This should not be possible and this behavior needs to be removed
 * NWR animation needs to be added back (wavy lines)
 * The hitbox of sliders for setting offsets needs to be increased to allow easier use. User should also be able to tap on the line to select directly instead of sliding.
 * The cabin temperature units mapping to user selection was erroring out occasionally, showing different unit than the outdoor temperature. To reproduce: set different units for 2 diferent profiles and switch between them
 * The enable/disable links to profiles should only work for profiles other than default. For default profiles, temporarily store the enable/disables per side but default back to on when user starts a new session or when default profile is not in use.
 * Setpoint memory per user was also not working properly. Edge cases might need revision

Upon receiving the updated UI, work with [~222116] to test all these bugs out and ensure they have been resolved

column724:
12/Mar/25 8:28 AM;ext.roopavathi.linga;-> Discussed with Ramesh and got the KT regarding the CSC introduction.
-> Started analysis on Bank swap example implementation, which covers the below sections
CSC code project preparation
Application code project preparation.
The analysis points are as followed:
-> In dual-bank devices, based on which bank is executable, that bank gets readexecute privileges and loses write or erase privileges. The other bank is readable, and writeable but not executable
-> Any firmware update can only be saved in the writeable bank in the current session but can never be executed
-> In bank-swappable configuration, the flash memory protections are automatically mirrored to both banks. This requests that CSC code must be identical across both BANK0 and BANK1 and the application code starts at the same offset address.
;;;
column725:
13/Mar/25 8:21 AM;ext.roopavathi.linga;Enable CSC (Customer Secure code) in Non Main region:
-> In document, there are options to enable CSC policy and Bank swap policy using Sysconfig tool.
-> When updating new Non Main configuration, erases the old configurations and updated new configuration will be programmed.
-> If suppose, any interruptions while re-program or erase operations, the device will get damaged.

Erase configurations:
-> There are some examples to configure Erase Main and Non Main regions with new configurations.


;;;

column724:
11/Mar/25 7:10 AM;ext.ramesh.jogi;The Customer Secure Code (CSC) is customer-owned software that configures additional advanced security settings after a BOOTRST and SYSRST.
The full set of features and execution
flow varies depending on the specific device used and features present on the device. Typically, customer owned secure code executes and implements additional security capabilities:
• Bank swap decision
• Secure firmware update
• Secure key storage
• Flash read-execute firewall
• Flash IP firewall
• SRAM write-execute mutual exclusion;;;
column725:
12/Mar/25 1:26 AM;ext.ramesh.jogi;The Csc execution of the device is divided into two distinct phases. A Privileged
and Unprivileged flow.
The privileged state must happen before the unprivileged state, and this is not possible to transition back to the privileged state without a BOOTRST.
Unprivileged mode has additional activated features, such as firewalls and the Read or Execute bank policy.The application is only ever run in the unprivileged mode.

The memory map shows the basic behavior of the Bank Swap, and how the CSC is executed.
Prior to INITDONE, the customer secure code always runs from PB0. Post INITDONE, the customer secure code is executed from either PB0 or PB1, depending on the bank swap execution. And, if the bank swap function executed, then the PB1 is re-mapped to address 0x0.;;;
column726: 13/Mar/25 5:35 AM;ext.ramesh.jogi;the NVM is configured to serve as two parallel blocks, the most important is the possibility to write on one bank without interrupting reading (and fetching instructions) from the other bank. This is the most important prerequisite to perform the updates without breaking the execution of the code from the program NVM.;;;

column1: [On Hold] Issue with Watchdog Timer on L1228 Board Causing Low Power State
column35:
The watchdog timer application setup has been created and validated on the PulsA L1228 PCB, the board goes into an unknown state upon flashing. This issue prevents flashing new code, and the device needs to be put into normal state by invoking the Boot Strap Loader (BSL) or scripts commands execution. Immediate attention is required to resolve this issue.

*Steps to Reproduce:*
 # Create and validate the watchdog timer application setup on the G3507 board.
 # Migrate the setup to the G3107 board and validate its functionality.
 # Migrate the same setup to the L1228 board.
 # Observe the board going into an unknown state, preventing further code flashing.

*Expected Result:* The watchdog timer application should work as expected on the L1228 board, similar to its performance on the G3507 and G3107 boards.

*Actual Result:* The L1228 board goes into an unknown state, requiring BSL invocation to return to normal state.

column1: Analysis of inputs given by TI for validating the Errors.
column35:
Need to analyze the way of validation for the below errors
 * Pin reset
 ** It is for reset by the NRST pin this can be pulled down externally
 * Power on reset / Low voltage reset
 ** Power on and off device or decrease the supply voltage to make sure it resets correctly
 * Watchdog 1 and 2 Reset
 ** Trigger a WWDT reset
 * Uncorrectable ECC error + Single BIT Flash ECC Error
 ** Can induce this error, see flashctrl_ecc_error_injection example
 * PLL is within desired tolerance (Implemented through FCC)
 ** This would not be triggerable, would verify with the CLKSTATUS register
 * Error in Flash
 ** Same as ECC errors

column1: Wakeup sleep module code changes for L-Series - Part 2
column35:
Continuing work on wakeup sleep implementation, 

resolve issue of Motor driver is not sleeping when RPM has set. the issue is that Config device 2 register of motor driver has to be rewrite to make motor driver sleep.
column44:
debugged on the issue, that motor driver is not sleeping when RPM is given. even when the PWM is set to zero, motor driver still in STANDBY mode. the issue is device config 2 register is changing when the PWM has set. to make the Motor driver SLEEP, device config 2 register has to be rewrite with SLEEP bit SET. 
while trying to rewrite the register on I2C, I2C facing some issue that it is not consistently writing the value to motor driver, when debugged found that I2C has to be reset before rewriting the register. ;12/Mar/25 2:23 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;32400
column45:
Tried to resolve the issue with I2C without resetting it. but there are some scenarios to be taken care from I2C side, such that sometimes I2C stuck in one state and even after some time spent in same state it doesnt goes to timeout. so, such scenarios are being taken care in latest changes.

meanwhile while debugging observed new issue that, when device config 2 register is set with the SLEEP mode, motor driver will go in sleep mode but when RPM is set to some non zero value, motor driver will wakeup but motor is not running. 
but when during initialization motor driver if device config 2register set with STANDBY mode, motor driver wont SLEEP and when RPM set to value motor runs fine.

conclusion is, when motor driver is initialized, it should initialize with STANDBY mode and when SLEEP request comes it should be initialized with SLEEP mode active. ;12/Mar/25 2:32 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;32400
column46:
The changes provided by Sravan for the I2C driver are working fine now. I2C can write the device config2 register without resetting the I2C. 

current implementation,

1) write device config 2 register with STANDBY mode when motor driver is initialized. This is required for motor driver to run when PWM set to non-zero value.

2) when SLEEP request receives, device config 2 register to be write with SLEEP mode SET. this makes the motor driver to sleep.




Note: When motor driver written with the SLEEP mode during initialization, then motor is not working on when RPM set to non-zero value. motor driver will wake-up but motor is not running.;12/Mar/25 1:22 PM;ext.amol.dokhle;32400
column47:
The issue with I2C has been resolved, recent changes are working fine now. motor driver register device config 2 can be written when sleep request comes. 

earlier I2C has to be reinitialize to write the Motor driver register but reinitialization is no more required.

after validation of wakeup sleep changes, sleep current is observed ~50uAmps. and motor works fine in all modes, 

when ECU is in RUN mode and RPM has been set motor will run at provided RPM, during motor run if SLEEP request comes, it will stop the motor and ECU will be put in SLEEP mode.

 

during validation, after analysis found that, there is sudden current drop for some micro secs, and it is raising at ~280uAmps. this is for very short time.

the main cause can be, when ECU wakeup after every 2 secs, to log the sleep time into system time. need to check after increasing this wakeup time so that ECU will be in SLEEP mode more time as much as possible.

this test need to be done.;14/Mar/25 4:50 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;32400
column668: The issue of motor driver in wakeup sleep feature has been resolved. motor is working fine now when RPM set to non-zero value. motor driver is going in sleep mode when sleep request received. motor speed will be set to zero and motor driver will go in Low Power mode,
column724:
12/Mar/25 2:24 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;debugged on the issue, that motor driver is not sleeping when RPM is given. even when the PWM is set to zero, motor driver still in STANDBY mode. the issue is device config 2 register is changing when the PWM has set. to make the Motor driver SLEEP, device config 2 register has to be rewrite with SLEEP bit SET. 
while trying to rewrite the register on I2C, I2C facing some issue that it is not consistently writing the value to motor driver, when debugged found that I2C has to be reset before rewriting the register. with this changes motor driver is going in SLEEP mode properly when sleep request received.;;;
column725:
12/Mar/25 2:33 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;Tried to resolve the issue with I2C without resetting it. but there are some scenarios to be taken care from I2C side, such that sometimes I2C stuck in one state and even after some time spent in same state it doesn't goes to timeout. so, such scenarios are being taken care in latest changes.

Meanwhile, while debugging observed new issue that, when device config 2 register is set with the SLEEP mode, motor driver will go in sleep mode but when RPM is set to some non-zero value, *motor driver will wake up, but motor is not running.* 
but when during initialization if device config 2 register set with STANDBY mode, motor driver wont SLEEP and *when RPM set to value motor runs fine.*

conclusion is, when motor driver is initialized, it should initialize with STANDBY mode and when SLEEP request comes it should be initialized with SLEEP mode active. ;;;
column726:
12/Mar/25 1:21 PM;ext.amol.dokhle;The changes provided by Sravan for the I2C driver are working fine now. I2C can write the device config2 register without resetting the I2C. 

current implementation,

1) write device config 2 register with STANDBY mode when motor driver is initialized. This is required for motor driver to run when PWM set to non-zero value.

2) when SLEEP request receives, device config 2 register to be write with SLEEP mode SET. this makes the motor driver to sleep.

 

*Note:* When motor driver written with the SLEEP mode during initialization, then motor is not working on when RPM set to non-zero value. motor driver will wake-up but motor is not running.;;;
column727:
14/Mar/25 4:49 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;The issue with I2C has been resolved, recent changes are working fine now. motor driver register device config 2 can be written when sleep request comes. 

earlier I2C has to be reinitialize to write the Motor driver register but reinitialization is no more required.

after validation of wakeup sleep changes, sleep current is observed ~50uAmps. and motor works fine in all modes, 

when ECU is in RUN mode and RPM has been set motor will run at provided RPM, during motor run if SLEEP request comes, it will stop the motor and ECU will be put in SLEEP mode.

 

during validation, after analysis found that, there is sudden current drop for some micro secs, and it is raising at ~280uAmps. this is for very short time.

the main cause can be, when ECU wakeup after every 2 secs, to log the sleep time into system time. need to check after increasing this wakeup time so that ECU will be in SLEEP mode more time as much as possible.

this test need to be done.

column44: Working on issue P109459-238;13/Feb/25 1:49 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;32400
column48:
Had a debug session with TI, as per their suggestion, SLEEP pin voltage of motor driver should be zero when PWM set to zero.

debug on this with Himanshu's support, after setting PWM to zero the voltage of SLEEP pin was ~2mV, which is considering close to zero only. but to confirm on this, already replied to TI and asked for the more details, if the followed procedure is correct and not missing anything.

meanwhile I crosschecked prepare APIs with entry to mid software as PulsA also using same modules. except motor control and PWM module.

yet need to dig in to find why motor driver is not sleeping. 

currently no hardware available for PulsA L-series at Hyderabad location so Himanshu is supporting if any debugging required.;26/Feb/25 12:54 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;32400
column49:
On G series, PulsA tested the same testing, setting PWM to zero and observing the SPEED pin, speed pin is setting to zero voltage is around ~2mV. observed same behavior as L-series.
but there is other issue observed that motor driver is behaving differently there. when current is ~9mAmps, which can be considered as motor driver is disabled (consumes ~28mAmps when enabled). when ECU has POR reset it normally enables the Motor driver and current goes to ~30mAmps.
seems motor driver is not initializing properly after software POR reset. issue to be debugged. same issue observed on L-series board as well when debugging in TI debug session on 27th Evening.;28/Feb/25 1:20 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;32400
column51:
Tests done on G series PulsA(as L series not yet available) - Build v00.03.000 + MCF_issue_fix

As per the last debugging, when PWM was sent from IAR, the Motor is running with given PWM speed. but when PWM has sent over the LIN BUS, the motor PWM is not updating. As the software using, wasn't having some latest changes.

Today 3rd March, tested with the latest G series software and integrated the changes from working build. the result were same for motor driver about sleep and wakeup. that motor is properly sleeping when PWM set to ZERO.

Test - 1

when ECU has POR reset, current is ~10mAmps.  to make sure if motor is still in RUN, tested by giving some PWM value from LIN. but the Motor is not running. CANoe is updating the PWM variable in CANoe window but issue is, it is not setting PWM on the motor driver side.

Test - 2

when ECU is reset, and PWM is set from IAR by updating the setPWM to some positive value. it runs the motor. 

 

When discussed with Himanshu, he informed that the build has some issue with G series recent build about LIN communication PWM set.

current plan is to go with L series PulsA boards and latest build, expected to receive boards today by 3rd Mrach it today;03/Mar/25 9:04 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;32400
column52:
5th March

L-series PulsA board (v00.04.0003 + wakeup sleep changes)

Test performed -

Changed motor driver device config 2 register configuration to 0xC000F807, as suggested by TI. Observed Motor driver is going in sleep mode. When ECU goes in Low Power Mode (STANDBY1), on regular multimeter observed 91uAmps current. same test was performed digital multimeter.

Zhangman Shi supported on validation on digital mulitmeter, 

observations are, 

1) When ECU is RUN mode, current reading is ~35mA.
2) when ECU is in Low Power Mode(STANDBY1) mode current rating is 53uAmps. (Attached images)
3) Motor is going sleep mode before ECU goes to SLEEP
4) when ECU wake up from LPM, the motor works fine.

above tests are performed multiple times and observations are same.;05/Mar/25 12:26 PM;ext.amol.dokhle;32400
column53:
6th March -

After validation on Himanshu's setup, issue has been observed.

when system is running and RPM set beyond 1000 RPM. the motor driver will wakeup and current goes to ~35mA. When ECU try to make it sleep by setting the PWM to zero, motor driver is not sleeping. even though ECU is in sleep the motor driver is awake.

current observation on issue is, when debug, found that the Device config register of motor driver has to be rewrite with the configuration to make it sleep.;07/Mar/25 1:14 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;32400
column668:
continuing work on the wakeup sleep implementation with part 2 ticket. 

issue is that motor driver is not sleeping when RPM has set. To resolve this, need to rewrite the device config 2 register.

column725:
13/Feb/25 5:39 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;Himanshu has validated this change, but the current is not dropping below 30mAmps in sleep mode. we could only observe 2mAmps drop after prepare API call. Current after prepare API should be around 1-2mApms. 

Validated that prepare APIs are same which are used in Entry to Mid, as MCAL is same for both PulsA and Entry to Mid.

The only difference and suspect for this current raise is motor driver. Seems it is not going in SLEEP mode. The issue faced on the G series PulsA.

need to investigate that if motor driver is properly going in SLEEP mode. ;;;

on regular mutlimeter i could see the current around 40uAmps but Himanshu's Setup is showing 28mAmps during SLEEP mode.

when Wakeup sleep task runs, PWM task won't run and it is possible that PWM is not set to zero which was set in PWM task. trying to set PWM in PWM prepare s that it will set before ECU going in LPM.

column729:
26/Feb/25 12:54 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;Had a debug session with TI, as per their suggestion, SLEEP pin voltage of motor driver should be zero when PWM set to zero.

debug on this with Himanshu's support, after setting PWM to zero the voltage of SLEEP pin was ~2mV, which is considering close to zero only. but to confirm on this, already replied to TI and asked for the more details, if the followed procedure is correct and not missing anything.

meanwhile I crosschecked prepare APIs with entry to mid software as PulsA also using same modules. except motor control and PWM module.

yet need to dig in to find why motor driver is not sleeping. 

currently no hardware available for PulsA L-series at Hyderabad location so Himanshu is supporting if any debugging required.;;;
column730:
28/Feb/25 4:48 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;*27th Feb - Had Debug session with TI on Motor Driver issue*

before this session TI has suggested to check the Motor driver DEVICE_CONFIG2 register configuration

earlier it was configured to - *0xC000B007* which will set motor driver to standby mode when PWM is zero, then TI suggested to change it to *0xC000F807* which will set motor driver to SLEEP mode.

with this change we are able to see the motor driver is going in SLEEP mode, and the current has been dropped to 500uAmps in SLEEP mode.

*Things to check after debug session,*

1) 500uAmps needs to be check where it is consuming during SLEEP mode.

2) when ECU has wakeup, seems modules/Motor driver are not initializing properly, ;;;
column731:
03/Mar/25 9:00 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;*Tests done on G series PulsA(as L series not yet available) - Build v00.03.000 + MCF_issue_fix*

As per the last debugging, when PWM was sent from IAR, the Motor is running with given PWM speed. but when PWM has sent over the LIN BUS, the motor PWM is not updating. As the software using, wasn't having some latest changes.

{*}Today 3rd March{*}, tested with the latest G series software and integrated the changes from working build. the result were same for motor driver about sleep and wakeup. that motor is properly sleeping when PWM set to ZERO.

*Test - 1*

when ECU has POR reset, current is ~10mAmps.  to make sure if motor is still in RUN, tested by giving some PWM value from LIN. but the Motor is not running. CANoe is updating the PWM variable in CANoe window but issue is, it is not setting PWM on the motor driver side.

*Test - 2*

when ECU is reset, and PWM is set from IAR by updating the setPWM to some positive value. it runs the motor. 

 

When discussed with Himanshu, he informed that the build has some issue with G series recent build about LIN communication PWM set.

*current plan is to go with L series PulsA boards and latest build, expected to receive boards today by 3rd Mrach it today*;;;
column732:
05/Mar/25 12:24 PM;ext.amol.dokhle;*5th March*

*L-series PulsA board (v00.04.0003 + wakeup sleep changes)*

*Test performed -*

Changed motor driver *device config 2* register configuration to *0xC000F807,* as suggested by TI. Observed Motor driver is going in sleep mode. When ECU goes in Low Power Mode (STANDBY1), on regular multimeter observed 91uAmps current. same test was performed digital multimeter.

*Zhangman Shi* supported on validation on digital mulitmeter, 

observations are, 

*1) When ECU is RUN mode, current reading is ~35mA.*

*2) when ECU is in Low Power Mode(STANDBY1) mode current rating is {color:#00875a}_+53uAmps+_{color}. (Attached images)*

*3) Motor is going sleep mode before ECU goes to SLEEP*

 *!multimeter.jfif|width=85,height=99!       !waveform_current.jfif|width=145,height=75!*

*4) when ECU wake up from LPM, the motor works fine.*

 

above tests are performed multiple times and observations are same.;;;
column733: 05/Mar/25 12:36 PM;ext.amol.dokhle;attached excel [^wakeupsleep_data.xlsx] of current observations of each module in L-series PulsA ;;;
column734:
07/Mar/25 1:19 AM;ext.amol.dokhle;*6th March -*

After validation on Himanshu's setup, issue has been observed.

when system is running and RPM set beyond 1000 RPM. the motor driver will wakeup and current goes to ~35mA. When ECU try to make it sleep by setting the PWM to zero, motor driver is not sleeping. even though ECU is in sleep the motor driver is awake.

current observation on issue is, when debug, found that the Device config register of motor driver has to be rewrite with the configuration to make it sleep.;;;

column51: More experiments for generating optimal LIN break signal with minimal CPU resources.  The TI MSPM0 UART has built-in timer capture/compare registers that are used to measure LIN sync pulses for autobaud detection.  The compare mode counter can also be used during transmission to help precisely time the generated LIN break signal.  This worked best.  The LIN break or LIN bus wakeup signal can be generated with a variable time using the UART break bit to assert the signal and the compare counter match interrupt to de-assert the signal.  The 16-bit counter match value sets the signal duration.  This counter is driven by the selected UART bus clock, plus the CLOCK_DIVRATIO register.;06/Dec/24 1:15 AM;jerry.girard;10800
column52: Developed compiler macros with equations to automatically calculate the number of LIN counter counts for a configured CPU clock rate and baud rate to generate the precise break and wakeup field timing. column724: 04/Feb/25 1:12 PM;jerry.girard;I started working on LIN Master features after the holiday but found that it was better to do the LIN auto baud detection feature first since the LIN Master would have dependencies on how the LIN driver front-end interrupt would handle the auto baud rate detection.  While pivoting to work on LIN auto baud detection, I had encountered a lot of technical issues with the LIN capture/compare counter peripheral built into the TI MSPM0 UART.  I had to get TI involved and develop a work-around, so I lost productivity and time.  I completed LIN auto baud rate detection feature several weeks ago and started back on LIN Master feature.  I am progressing on the LIN master features but am behind due to the technical issues I had with the LIN auto baud detection.  I also had trouble with LIN master because the original LIN stack was designed only for LIN slave.  As a result, I had to take special care and time for the design updates so I can implement the LIN master functionality without make a mess or breaking the existing LIN slave features.  There is a lot of common code between master and slave.  I had to adjust some slave functions and data structures to share with the master functionality.  There is also a lot of additional subtle functionality to LIN master that one does not think about, like retry, schedule table arbitration with diagnostics, diagnostic interleave mode, etc.  The diagnostic portion of LIN master added a lot of additional functionality and complexity.  It is all progressing well, but my timing has slipped by a few weeks to complete the LIN master functionality.;;;

column1: Calculated CRC is not Matching with the CRC value Received from the Response Frame.
column8: 109016 ECU GENERAL MOTORS SDV V284 HVSM LIN IO Extender 2027
column35:
Issue Found:

Calculated CRC is not matching with the actual CRC received from the Response frame which is calculating the 7 Bytes of data in the Response Frame.

How to Reproduce:



Steps Followed:

1.Turn ON the cfg.
2.Send the LIN frames from the LIN scheduler.
3.Validate the CRC value for 7 bytes of data in each Response frame.

Expected Reslts:

1.Cfg shold turn ON
2.LIN frames should transmit in the trace window.
3.Calculated CRC value should match with the CRC value received from the Response frame.
column724: 12/Mar/25 5:26 PM;lee.liu;Hello John, my CRC implementation is in lif_cfg.c on Github [Gentherm/109016_GM_V284_HVSM_LIN_IO_EXTENDER_DUAL_SEAT_ECU|https://github.com/Gentherm/109016_GM_V284_HVSM_LIN_IO_EXTENDER_DUAL_SEAT_ECU]. Please work with Varunkishore and Kaustubh on this ticket. I think we just need to calculate a 7-byte CRC, not 8 bytes as currently implemented. But you can have a look and we can discuss if you have questions. Thanks!;;;

column35:
Check if the blower diagnostics are implemented by the platform team. If not, please implement per the HSIS v2. If yes, please test the implementation and ensure correct fault values are reported on LIN.

With the blower output not connected to anything, AggLtRow1BkVntLoSdFlt should be 1

With the blower output pulled to Battery via the 2k resistor, short the output to Ground, AggLtRow1BkVntLoSdFlt should be 1

With the blower output pulled to Battery via the 2k resistor, short the output to Battery, AggLtRow1BkVntLoSdFlt should be 2

column44: Working on issue P108340-1095;10/Mar/25 5:59 AM;Kilian.Dierig;3600

column35:
Here all activities are listed like:
 * team meetings
 * workshops
 *

Perform short circuit test on STCU:
 * Connect car battery and power supply set to 14V and with 20A+ current limit.
 * Leave battery charged this way for 1h
 * Then connect STCU via a 20-40A blade fuse (smaller fuse can be used, but it has to be checked that the fuse is not blown during test; higher rated fuse can't be used, it would be quite dangerous). If fuse is blown during the test, a higher current rating fuse shall be used and test shall be repeated.
 * Wiring harness should be short and capable to carry more than 100A short circuit current (not continous, that would not fit to the connector)
 * Turn on heater for 1 minute with 100% duty
 * Introduce short circuit (at least 100A short current)
 * Remove short and reset ECU
 * Repeat short for 5 times total
 * Remove short, reset ECU and with heater turned off, introduce the short
 * Turn on heater to the short circuit for 5 times
 * Remove short and confirm ECU functionality (after reset)
 * Remove ECU from housing and check for any damage
 * Create test report and upload to PDM as simple test

Use STCU with housing, connector and final harness. Harness should be trimmed to shortest possible length.
Epic for all engeneering lead activities not dedicated to milestones

column724: 04/Mar/25 5:35 AM;David.Simon;Workshop on 03-04.04.2025.;;;

column35:
In the DV we faced the issue that the voltage drop in the STCU is to high. Customer will accept the diviation for this. In order to get green results in the PV we need to calculate the worst case voltage drop.

 

*Current definition:*

For the power supply line, the voltage drop will be lower than 0,1V.

This is measured between the input pin and the heater output pin of the STCU (see figure below)

!image-2025-02-26-11-23-12-278.png|width=172,height=131!

In the DV tests we see values from 0,14 V to 0,16 V.

 

*The calculations should consider:*
 * smart high side Rdson change over lifetime
 * second shigh side MOSFET Rdson change over lifetime
 * PCBA trace change over lifetime
 * Lifetime is 15 years with 14600 activations

column728:
17/Mar/25 4:45 AM;Kilian.Dierig;[~226502] the lifetime of the STCU is 3300 hours with 14600 activations. The expected distribution is:
 * Tmin @-40°C 1320h (40%)
 * Tnom @+23°C 1320 (40%)
 * Tmax @+85°C 660 (20%)

If you need additional information please reach out to me;;;

column35:
The Hungarian Test lab asked some help with logging the NTC temperatures during heat up test with a Lipowsky tool (BabyLIN RC-II). I have supported them before with a BabyLIN configuration and that needed further adjustments.

The task is not easy as there is literately no help or description on how to log, so it has to be found out iteratively and through example programs.

The priority is high as Adient is forming their requirements in collaboration with us, to have heating regulation within +/- 1degC.
column44:
- Setting up 2 ECUs with SW0.2.2.
      -  Checking heating control mechanism. for normal SetTemp and High Resolution.
      -  Sending summary email. 
     - Finding a BabyLIN and getting it working with an old sdf file. Catching up on operation of BabyLIN config.;05/Mar/25 3:26 AM;Balazs.Nagy;28800
column45:
-Checking what is the best way to  log data amongst many options. It needed many iterations to find out, how to have a defined time between datapoints, becaue the BabyLIN does not have an online help (actually no help at all), so normally things have to be done iteratively. 
     - There is also a signal plot option for live data monitoring, many difficulties for setting that up, as the display, only starts if there is at least one of the signals changed.
     -  In addition I have created a macro to convert the raw temperature data into degree Celsius, where I had difficulties for setting up signed integer values in the SessionConf and also there was a problem with the number of data bits used, as the signed integer only goes up to 127, whereas some calculations needed to extend to higher values.  The main problem was that the calculation inside the BabyLIN uses hex or binary numbers and the conversion between positive and negative numbers has to be taken care of, by using the necessary number of data bits. 
    - I have updated the HowTo file for the testlab, with all the information learned and sent them a saved config file for data logging, which can be loaded into SimpleMenu.;05/Mar/25 3:27 AM;Balazs.Nagy;28800

column1: Check minimum distance of PCB tracks on both sides of PCB
column35:
*Description:*

There was a meeting on 20.02.2025 with Michael Seifert, Johannes Grau, Jens Schuhmacher, Felix Winter, Simon Seiler where we decided to check whether it would make sense *to evaluate* if we can partially or completely remove the coating from the "4N0-blower"(See meeting notes [https://confluence.gentherm.com/x/hbOzD] ).

It was agreed on to do so. As VW has a minimum distance requirement for PCB tracks in order to potentially leave the coating we need to check the distances on the PCB.

 

*Task:*
 # Check where we have the lowest PCB track distances on the PCB
 # Measures and report how big this distances are

 

*Definiton of Done:*
 # A screenshot from the PCB design for top and bottom showing the places with the lowest PCB track distance (distance between the tracks)
 # The screenshot shall contain the information on how big this distances are

column1: [71X][SCMK][SCML] A Horizontal Hall sensor STG keeps the module awake
column35:
*Observed behavior*

A Horizontal Hall sensor STG(Short to Ground) keeps the module awake, preventing it from remaining at "Deep-Sleep" state. 

*Expected behavior*

A Horizontal Hall sensor STG shouldn't keep the module awake

A Horizontal Hall sensor STG shouldn't prevent the module from remaining at Deep-Sleep state. 

*Analysis:*

The fault "Horizontal Hall Sensor STG" is triggering the wake-up interrupt assigned to the Power Pitch Switch. 

!image-2025-03-05-09-32-53-320.png|width=515,height=278!

Support from HW team required to understand the why and what.

*Proposal:*

1. Remove the PowerPitch switch wake up source interrupts. The Power Pitch Switch cannot be a wake-up source as this isn't supported by HW. 

2. Further investigations to validate the root cause are needed, once the root cause is confirmed a good practice will be to add a delay between the Port configuration changes and "enabling the Wake-up Interrupts"

 

*Temp Results:*

The behavior isn't seen if a delay is added before executing "Enable_WakeupInterrupts". Delay manually added via a breakpoint. 

*!image-2025-03-05-09-25-51-286.png|width=498,height=109!*

column1: Verification of DTC issues during On-Demand Self Test
column35:
*SW version:* R05.05.01

*Test setup:* HUN VT System with complete seat and steering column loads (only hardstop motors)

 

+*Description:*+ {color:#00875a}The following test steps were executed 25 times to trigger any Hall Sensor DTC, but there was no any Hall Sensor DTC at all.{color} I used only medium power, hard stopped motors for ST_Tele, ST_Tilt and Pedal.

 

+*Preconditions:*+

a. Send DID write request [ 2E DE 07 80 0C ]   

b. Send DID write request [ 2E DE 09 51 59 68 58 24 ]  

c. Send DID write request [ 2E DE 14 FE 05 06 FE FE 02 14 02 00 ]  

 

+*Test Steps:*+

a. Move *ST_Tele, ST_Tilt and Pedal* motor fully *rearward / downward*

b. Request the Routine Starts *[ 31 01 02 02 ]*

    Wait for 30 sec

c. Request the Routine Results *[ 31 03 02 02 ]* 

 

+*Expected Result:*+
a. Observe the  *ST_Tele, ST_Tilt and Pedal* motor move all the way rearward / downward and stop due to hard stop

b. ECU Sends Positive response  *[ 71 01 02 02 ]*

c. ECU Sends Positive response  *[ 71 03 02 02 ]*

 

+*Actual Result:*+

a. Observe the  *ST_Tele, ST_Tilt and Pedal* motor move all the way rearward / downward and stop due to hard stop

b. ECU Sends Positive response  *[ 71 01 02 02 ]*

c. ECU Sends Positive response  *[ {color:#00875a}71 03 02 02{color} ]*

column1: Code Improvement - To resolve PRB and heater override flag status conflict
column35:
Creating additional ticket to resolve one more heater override flag status update that happens during the end of PRB movement.
This happens because of our current PRB logic, when PRB movement is completed, the smp_ctrl.current_dir == STOP but there is some delay because of model update to indicate that PRB state is DEPLOYED/STOWED, due to this delay there is brief time where the heater override is cleared by PRB as the current direction is changed to STOP but it is immediately set back because the low layer still thinks its not been deployed

The goal of this ticket is to ensure that heater override flag does not fluctuate during PRB movement

column1: [U71X][DSM][PRB] Aging counter resets to 0 randomly and PRB Motor and Hall Sensor DTCs does not age
column35:
{+}SW version{+}: R05.05

{+}Tested on{+}: VT System in US

+*Test steps:*+

a. Set PwRnngBoardMde_D_Rq to OFF

c. Perform a Short to Batt to  *Right_PRB_Hall_sense_Motor* as  *STOWED/STOW* during the motion

d. Move PRB motors and Read DTC

g. Remove the short to battery

i. Perform Ignition Cycle and Read DTC

j. Perform Ignition cycle for 39 times

k. Set PwRnngBoardMde_D_Rq to OFF and wait for 4 sec

l. Read DTC status with aging counter

 

+*Expected result:*+
d. ECU sends Positive response, containing   DTC ( Motor Output(Short to Batt))  with Status Byte as 0x0B [ 59 02 CB    *0x500915*      0B ]

i. ECU sends Positive response, containing   DTC ( Motor Output(Short to Batt))  with Status Byte as 0x08 [ 59 02 CB       *0x500915*       08 ]

l. ECU sends a Positive response, where XX is the Counter that goes from 0 to 39 and then 0

 

+*Actual result:*+
d. Value of PwRnngBoardMde_D_Stat signal is OFF

i. Self Test is Successful, value 107 learned

l. Counter resets to 0 randomly in between 0 to 39 and DTC does not age

column642: Wait for the read operation of BRG_CTRL1 to complete before proceeding to read BRG_CTRL2 register value. If the first read fails, abort the second read
column673:
In Sgd_UpdateBrgCtrl() function, there is a SPI Read functions used to read BRG_CTRL1 and BRG_CTRL2 register values. 
If the Sgd_ReadRegister() returns TIME_OUT value indicating unsuccessful SPI read operation of BRG_CTRL1 register, we shall ignore this TIMEOUT and continue to read the BRG_CTRL2 register value. This shall result in a DET tool error
column724:
14/Jan/25 12:32 PM;sangeetha.gundami; !Error_DueTo_Timeout_on_BRG_CTRL1Read.png|thumbnail! 
;;;
column725:
13/Mar/25 12:40 PM;sangeetha.gundami;After debugging latest SCMK software, figured out that the issue happened because of 
*SpiSequence_SGD2_Diag* job sequence initiated during the initialization task , 
Sgd_Init().
Captured SPI log with Chip select for U10 SGD2, and found that the jobs in *SpiSequence_SGD2_Diag* was never sent on SPI bus when it gets timed out trying to Read BRG_CTRL1 register.  !image-2025-03-13-12-47-28-270.png!
Since we are ignoring the return status of this BRG_CTRL1 register and proceeding with another Read BRG_CTRL2 register, which happens to be same SPI job, DET error is triggered. ;;;
column726:
14/Mar/25 9:40 AM;sangeetha.gundami;Further more debugging at SPi.c file level found that:

1. When  *SpiSequence_SGD2_Diag* is initiated by initialization function(
Sgd_SingleInit{*}),{*} the SPI message was not sent and queued because HW unit is busy, so it just returns SPI_OK and starts executing End sequence notification which is *SGD2_Diag_Runnable.* 
*!image-2025-03-14-09-39-14-006.png!*
 
In this screenshot it enters the else codition where it just returns ok without doing actual SGD2 Job sequence transmission;;;
column727:
17/Mar/25 11:16 AM;sangeetha.gundami;Verified SPI communication on other DSM variant, and found that it had a similar be haviour. Refer to attached SPI log from DSM variant, it can be seen that not all the jobs in  *SpiSequence_SGD4_Diag was transmitted (Captured on U35* SGD). Also sometimes the read registers BRG_CTRL1 and BRG_CTRL2 was missed in the end sequence notification. 

The MOSI sequence should have this below sequence . But in the logs it can be seen this sequence is missing.[^U35_J2Open_onPowerUp_11V.csv]

0x40 Read IC_STAT1

0x45 Read IC_STAT2

0x41 Read VDS_STAT1

0x42 Read VDS_STAT2

0x43 Read VGS_STAT1

0x44 Read VGS_STAT2

0x49 Read BRG_CTRL1

0x4A Read BRG_CTRL2

 

So the missing data on SPI is happening on all SGDs and all variants. 

 ;;;
column729:
17/Mar/25 11:28 AM;sangeetha.gundami;After doing some research in available API calls to SPI interface, found that *Spi_GetSequenceResult* API should be able to notify if the Job sequence did not transmit all the jobs . Now validating if this function is properly used in sgd_cfg.c file , and if the incorrect usage of this function was resulting in not getting notification for the missed jobs in the SPI sequence.

!image-2025-03-17-11-25-56-577.png!;;;
column730: 18/Mar/25 10:34 AM;sangeetha.gundami;Sample code indicated that *Spi_GetSequenceResult()* always returned value SPI_SEQ_OK, even when some jobs where missing on SPI bus.  Clearing seeing that jobs in *SpiSequence_SGD2_Diag or* *SpiSequence_SGD3_Diag or* *SpiSequence_SGD4_Diag and* *SpiSequence_SGD5_Diag ,* had issues with not all jobs sent on SPI bus. Still unable to figure out why this is happening;;;
column731: 18/Mar/25 10:37 AM;sangeetha.gundami;Tried *InterruptibleSequence* parameter value.. The existing implementation has this parameter value set to SPI_TRUE for the sequences *SpiSequence_SGD2_Diag or* *SpiSequence_SGD3_Diag or* *SpiSequence_SGD4_Diag and* {*}SpiSequence_SGD5_Diag{*}. Tried a sample code by changing this value to SPI_FALSE, but resulted in no change in behaviour. Probably because none of the Jobs had priority.;;;

column1: PRBs move full travel when hall signal is missing
column35:
Steps to replicate

Configure module

Learn PRB's

Operate PRB's to ensure functionality

Remove Hall wire from PRB

Command PRB' Out/IN

Expected behavior:

PRB moves for 500mS and stops each command event

 

Observed behavior:

PRB moves full travel and an audible click is heard as the PRB try's to drive to the position.
column44: Working on issue FDSM5-8327;03/Jan/25 7:39 AM;222012;28800
column724:
07/Nov/24 1:57 PM;222012;It's a known issue. And we have more root causes.

*1.* STG Inc-Val is 24. STB-OC Inc-Val is 12. 
It means that the PRB has to wait for 6 or 11 seconds which is too long for the hall sensor DTC.
The PRB will move without sense for 6 or 11 seconds. If we reach the end position with hall sensor STG in one second,
the PRB will try to move in the same direction for 5 or 10 seconds. The current consumption will be high for this 5 - 10 sec. 

As far as I know, these Inc values will be incremented to 127. 
Jineesh arranges with Ford.

*2.* We actually reached the DEPLOYED position, but the hall count was zero because of hall sensor fault. - as you wrote in your test case too
The PRB wants to reach the end of position - which is 625. But the 0 hall count position is not in the obstacle detection zone,
this is why we have high current consumption, and audible click is heard.
Because the hall sense count is 0, we are not in the obstacle detection zone.
If we make a hall sensor issue during the movement, the PRB will work well, because the hall count is in the range of the obstacle detection zone 
and the PRB will go back to STOWED position. It is enough time to detect the DTC.

And when we reach the end position with 0 hall count and there is high current consumption, we skip the hall sensor DTC check in the code. 
So we have only one motion to detect these DTCs.

Where did the 500ms duration to stop come from in your test?;;;
column725: 07/Nov/24 3:54 PM;222872;!image-2024-11-07-15-53-25-614.png! Currently our "steps" for other motors is 500mS. ;;;
column727:
07/Jan/25 9:51 AM;222012;Must be modified in DaVinci, because at the moment it takes 11 and 6 seconds to activate the DTC with a rate of 1000ms. During this time, only the DTC detection debounce counter will be modified.
I will modify these DaVinci numbers and test them, whether it is then activated properly.;;;

column1: Stall Detection Logic is interfering with Hall Sense DTC Detection
column35:
Stall Detection Logic is interfering with Hall Sense DTC Detection logic. Therefore, Hall sensor DTCs take more than 1 motor activation to confirm.

See linked bugs for a complete list of all affected DTCs.
column44: Working on issue FDSM5-8302;31/Dec/24 5:45 PM;223818;14400
column724:
11/Feb/25 2:37 PM;223818;New implementation divides the motor running time in two: start-up and running. The start-up is limited to the first 50ms of the motor motion.

The running section is everything beyond the 50ms. The goal of the startup check is to block the count-based stall detection during the first 50ms at motor start.

There are 5 main changes:

1. Add hall fault testing at start-up. Using the idea that at least 1 hall pulse must be seen during the first 50ms otherwise there's an issue with the hall sensor. Removes the need to activate the motor multiple times to debounce a hall related DTC.

2. Only allow the hall fault to be tested if the current conditions are met. This prevents healing a hall fault when the motor stalls (current is outside the testable area).

3. When a hall fault is seen, instead of blocking all the stall detection (counts + current) only block the counts-based approach and allow a current based stall detection.

4. Add the capability to test the hall sensor while running after the initial motor counts.

5. Update pitch hall sensor OC and STB debounce counter from 0 to 4. This allows to move the motor for 4 seconds without a retry.

 

 

Tested OC, STB and STG with SCMK horiz and pitch hall sensors([^Logs.7z]). 
 - STG DTC triggers in 1 sec with no retrying. 
 - STB and OC triggers in 4 seconds with no retrying.  
 - STG, STB and OC faults DTCs don't heal while fault present and motor(horiz and pitch) stalling. 
 - STG, STB and OC faults DTCs don't  heal while fault not present and motor stalling. 
 - TG, STB and OC faults DTCs heal when fault not present and motor running with no stall, no multiple retries required. 
 - After SelfTest run the DTCs are logged correctly when fault present and not seen when there's no fault. 
 - AbsPosLearning routine completes succesfully. ;;;

column1: Hall DTC's can be triggered falsely during self test when motors are at rearward hardstop
column35:
When Specifically steering and pedal, But in theory all hall motors, are at the rearward hardstop during selftest, Short to battery or short to ground DTC's for the hall circuit are triggered during selftest.

 

Test procedure:

Set motor to full rearward hardstop

Run Selftest

Expected results: No DTC's

Observed results: Short DTC for hall sense circuit.

 

Need to adjust DTC implementation to not trigger the DTC when the motor is at rearward hardstop.
