column726:
02/Dec/24 3:00 AM;ext.sayyadranees.a;Issue is reproducible.

 

Root cause:

Here always satisfying the if condition in the function

static U16 smp_check_hall_sensor_fault(U8 motor_index, U16 Count, U16 Current)

File name :smp_ctrl_cfg.c

 

  if(  ( Count   <= smpSrv_countErr[motor_index])  

  &&( Current > smpSrv_under_current[motor_index] )

  &&( Current < smpSrv_max_inrush_current[motor_index]))

 

!If condition_Satisfying.png|width=469,height=318!

 

This is the reason the Hall DTC always set.

Monitored the variable Current ,smpSrv_max_inrush_current[motor_index],

smpSrv_under_current[motor_index]in the debugger.

 

 

{color:#001080}Current {color}{color:#000000}> {color}{color:#001080}smpSrv_under_current{color}{color:#3b3b3b}[{color}{color:#001080}motor_index{color}{color:#3b3b3b}] and {color}{color:#001080}Current {color}{color:#000000}< {color}{color:#001080}smpSrv_max_inrush_current{color}{color:#3b3b3b}[{color}{color:#001080}motor_index{color}{color:#3b3b3b}]){color}

Always satisfied in all conditions(Short to ground,Open circuit,No fault injected).

But I observed that the variable Count randomly changing its behavior(sometimes 0,36,29..).

 

Image with No Normal condition

!Image with no fault1.png|width=385,height=313!

!Image with no fault2.png|width=400,height=314!

 

Open circuit

!Image with open circuit.png|width=425,height=398!

 

Short to GND

!Image with Short to GND.png|width=449,height=400!

 

I observed one more if condition unexpected behavior.

if(hallFaultTestCounts[hallSensorIndex] >= hall_sensor_diag_period).

Here This is a static array, and it will hold the value either 0 or 1. The variable

hall_sensor_diag_period holds the value 40 if self-test (1>=40) is ongoing. Here also this condition is getting satisfied. Investigating on this.;;;
column727:
06/Jan/25 10:48 AM;ext.sayyadranees.a;Root cause :

Here count variable will be 0 always if the hall motor does not move or if the hall sensor having fault.

If we run self- test routine, motor will run in both direction (rearward and forward direction)

So here if I keep the motor at rearward hardtop and run self -test, The motor will not move. Because already it is in rearward hardstop.it will not move. Therefore, the count will be 0 and always satisfies the if condition and set the DTC .

 

!image-2025-01-06-21-11-22-425.png|width=465,height=245!

 

Here I analyzed the code and  as per the *FD33,* I noticed that rearward hard-stop value for few motors  is *-32768* and for others is {*}0{*}.

!image-2025-01-06-21-12-03-954.png|width=389,height=408!

But practically I'm unable to reach this position even if the motor is in rearward hard stop position.

When I move the motor to the rearward hard stop, I'm observing different hard stop values.

!image-2025-01-06-21-12-31-183.png|width=579,height=308!

 

!image-2025-01-06-21-13-36-519.png|width=589,height=320!

 

!image-2025-01-06-21-14-07-935.png|width=599,height=340!

If I get constant count value when the motor is in rearward hard position, I can modify the if condition and it will be fixed as shown in screenshot below.

 

!image-2025-01-06-21-14-56-725.png|width=587,height=307!

 

We can implement this solution but might be complicated.

So, need to find the solution in other way.;;;
column728:
09/Feb/25 11:48 PM;ext.sayyadranees.a;[~222894]  The issue was not reproduced in the remote setup *L21FFQH5Y2* in the beginning. Because setup was connected to *PSM* and I was unable to reproduce the issue on this. Then       *Juan Manuel Garcia Huerta* was working on *SCML/SCMK,* and he was using the setup which was connected second row seat with the remote setup *L21FFQH5Y2.* After his activity I tested with him on that remote setup but issue was not reproduced.

 

When I was testing on setup at @cognizant, I was able to see the issue sometimes (reproducing the issue was not consistent). I referred the *DID FD33* which has hardstop values for all motors.

As per the rearward stop value mentioned in the DID FD33 I was unable to reach. Everytime the hardstop value was different. So implemented as per this {*}DID FD33{*}.But it didn't work.

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-39-19-479.png|width=496,height=520!

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-39-36-245.png|width=489,height=256!

 

Then I had a discussion with Manuel regarding this. He said that we cannot reach this hardstop value practically as per the DID {*}FD33{*}.During this discussion I was testing on *pedal motor* and cannot be reach *-32768* for pedal motor(I was expecting to reach count -36768 rearward stop for pedal motor as per the DID DE33).

 

  In the local setup we have only 3 motor in the Frame. So we came to a conclusion that it might be a second row frame. So He suggested me to test SCML/SCMK software. Because second row has hall sensor for horizontal motor. Then I tested on horizontal motor. As per the DID FD33 rearward hard stop value for *horizontal motor*  is {*}0{*}. But it was going beyond that.

!image-2025-02-13-13-42-20-473.png|width=529,height=280!

 

I started working on another proposal. He gave me the input that when the motor is at rearward hardstop if we run the self-test that time the motor will not move in rearward direction. Because already it is at hard stop, so the motor will not move. As per the discussion input from Manuel, I implemented the Proposal 2.

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-43-04-202.png|width=553,height=286!

 

But the count was updating as per the movement. Means the motor is moving both the direction. There was little movement in rearward direction. So this proposal also didn't work. I updated this to Manuel.

But one thing I observed that if the difference between *smp_data[motor_index].smp_current_pos* and  *smp_data[motor_index].smp_desired_pos* is very less then the issue was reproducing{*}.{*}

When I updated my observation to the Manuel he suggested me  that try to identify the rearward count value and forward count value first.

 

Before running self- test routine

!image-2025-02-13-13-44-32-574.png|width=438,height=232!

 

After running self- test routine

!image-2025-02-13-13-45-29-011.png|width=456,height=230!

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-46-25-868.png|width=467,height=236!

!image-2025-02-13-13-47-05-047.png|width=466,height=246!

I did as per his suggestion. So, I modified the code (for testing only) to identify the count for rearward side movement and forward side movement. This was done to identify the approximate count which is affecting this issue.

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-48-30-310.png|width=488,height=249!

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-49-07-987.png|width=441,height=604!

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-49-41-814.png|width=444,height=568!

 

I tested for 10 iterations but 4 times I observed the issue. But in those 4 iterations, before running self-test count was same and after running self-test also count was same. Then again, I tested but issue was not reproduced.

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-50-44-769.png|width=516,height=273!

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-51-19-119.png|width=527,height=266!

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-52-06-337.png|width=514,height=271!

 

Again discussion happened with Manuel. I informed him and tested together. The observation was Sometimes the count was getting stuck and reproducing the issue. It means when  motor rearward hardstop, I ran self-test that time the count was getting stuck and triggering the  DTC {*}0x967f11({*}Second Row Slide Motor Hall Sensor DTC) *.*

Ater this I moved the motor, and motor was running forward or rearward both the side, but Hall count was always 0(no change in count even motor is moving rearward or forward).

 

He asked me to reflash the software and check the motor movement with count without running self-test. I re-flashed the same software and  I did not run self-test then count was updating in both the direction as per the movement .

 

After this he suggested me to change the duty cycle by referring {*}DID DE33{*}.I  tested by setting PWM({*}DE33{*}) by making duty cycle from *100% to 54% as his suggested.*

Configured the DID DE33 and kept the horizontal motor at rear word hard stop then I ran self-test .Count was updating as per the motor movement  but Issue was not reproduced. After testing these many times issue was not reproduced( issue was not consistent).

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-53-04-745.png|width=500,height=265!

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-53-36-381.png|width=507,height=288!

 

!image-2025-02-13-13-54-09-037.png|width=536,height=620!;;;

column35:
*Update 07/29/24 ==============================================*

During testing it's noted that in all variants the "Routine 0x2072 - Learn Seat Soft Stop" information in Subsystem Specific Diagnostic Specification (part 2) has missing information in fields "Entry criteria" and "Exit Criteria" and has an incorrect value in field "Maximum Routine Run Time", see image 1 in comments.

Seat stop learn configuration;
Routine 2072 always aborts, DTC always gets set; unable to clear after setting
column44: Working on issue FDSM5-7903;29/Jul/24 5:11 PM;223818;10800
column724:
25/Jul/24 2:38 PM;223818; 

*SW UPDATE 29/07/24==========================================*

Tested with [~andranik.melikyan]  in Northville VT system and conclusion is that the DTC behaves as expected and there's no SW issue. 

As long as routine 0x2072 doesn't finish successfully, the DTC 0x972300 is logged accordingly to its parameters (test period, increase counter, etc.).
Moreover:
 - After $14 runs, if fault remains (Seat Soft Stop not learned) then DTC will be relogged as 0x0B once fault is matured. 
 - After $14 runs, if fault not present (Seat Soft Stop learned) then DTC will not be logged. 

During this testing it's noted that in all variants the "Routine 0x2072 - Learn Seat Soft Stop" information in Subsystem Specific Diagnostic Specification (part 2) has missing information in fields "Entry criteria" and "Exit Criteria" and has an incorrect value in field "Maximum Routine Run Time", see image 1. 

This is relevant to the DTC 0x972300 as it depends on the result of routine 0x2072 which cannot be run if its "Entry Criteria" isn't met. Based on this, the ticket is reassigned to [~michael.manquen].  

Image 1. 

!image-2024-07-29-16-41-43-579.png|width=744,height=408!

*==========================================*

[~andranik.melikyan]  Can you, please, share the steps to reproduce the issue? 

From my side I see the DTC 0x972300 is matured after 32s, can be cleared out with $14 and if the fault is present, it will be relogged again after 32 seconds. 

Routine 2072 must complete the learning in order to heal the DTC.  ;;;

column1: Horiz motor short to battery verification
column35:
During Horizontal motor short to battery testing the DTC detection time is 2-4 seconds, which is not a problem.

But our finding is that on the manual and on the VT system the current consumption during this test is increased by 0.2-0.5 A compared to the base current consumption, which means that the output is not inactive as it is specified in the FuSa RQs in case of any type of Fault.

So please confirm if this is a real finding (R5.3.X):

-DTC detection time 2-4 seconds is too high

-increased current consumption is not allowed during this test

 

PS: On two ECUs this behavior occurs 8-20 A current increase, so these ECUs are damaged, and if don't change this behavior, our new ECUs will be damaged too.

 

 

*With R3.9 this issue is not present at all, the DTC detection is happening immediately.*

 

*[~saurabh.bhatia] , [~223535] :* Please leave your comments if I missed something.

 

Test steps:

 
 # Request Horiz motor movement
 # Apply Short To battery on Horiz motor (try before the motion is started and during motion is in progress)
 # Read DTCs
 # Remove the Short to Battery
 # Stop requesting the motion

Expected result:
 # Horiz motor is moving
 # Motor stopped, or motion inhibited, current consumption is not increased (under 0.3A)
 # Horiz motor short to Battery DTC present with status 0B

Actual result:
 # Horiz motor is moving
 # Motor stopped, or motion inhibited, current consumption is increased (0.5-0.8A, 8-20A with damaged ECUs)
 # Horiz motor short to Battery DTC present with status 0B (if the voltage drop is not so high due to short to battery current, that the ECU is executing a Reset. In this case the ECU is starting a resetting loop with high Battery current peaks)

 

[~michael.seck] : Please, if you confirm that SW change is needed with this topic, than set this bug to unassigned with your comments or assign it to [~222894] 

 

Logs are attached in the linked issues.

column737:
11/Feb/25 1:01 AM;ext.sayyadranees.a;[~222894] [~shobhit.mahajan] The issue able to reproduce in PSM variant. 

!image-2025-02-11-10-31-11-700.png|width=558,height=296!

I compared the code with DSM variant for the signal  {*}SeatAutoSavDrv_D_Stat.{*}But  here I observed that one if condition is commented.

!image-2025-02-11-11-08-15-771.png|width=586,height=388!

I think in PSM also need to comment or remove that if condition.

!image-2025-02-11-11-10-35-891.png|width=609,height=311!

Because once the application starts running 
*CanSignalTxConfirm[SeatAutoSavPsngr_D_St]* update to *COMSTAT_TX_CONFIRMED.* But here comparing with {*}COMSTAT_TX_IDLE.{*}So the if condition will not satisfy at all here.
 
!image-2025-02-11-11-18-44-306.png|width=540,height=259!
 
Here *PrvCanSignalTx[SeatAutoSavPsngr_D_St]* should update according to the RTE call 
Rte_DRead_SeatAutoSavDrvDStatOutCAN_SeatAutoSavDrvDStatOutCAN( ).
This RTE call is same for both DSM as well as PSM. Means Data dictionary for the signal *SeatAutoSavPsngr_D_St* and *SeatAutoSavDrv_D_Stat* is same.  This RTE call is updating properly. But the signal *SeatAutoSavPsngr_D_St* is not updating at all. Need to check configuration once.

column1: Transition of Gergely D, Tamas SzaboSzucs and Shanta Holakall
column35: Please provide transition plan for Gergely D, Tamas SzaboSzucs and Shanta Holakall with new resource names, ramp up/ramp down plan.

Test system: VT system Hungary, PRB replaced with Seat motors

SW version: R05.02.00

Main issue:
Self test (Learning) not aborted in case of *high voltage, kick switch, high vehicle speed, Car mode Transport*

Test steps:

a) Send default settings
b) Run self test
c) During motion inject fault

Expected result:

a) Positive response
b) Self test started
c) Self test stopped, DTC is present

Actual result:

a) Positive response
b) Self test started
c) Self test not stopped, DTC is not present even if self test is not started, or aborted, or executed.

Note: For details check the linked results.
